-- British Airways, Investec, Carillion, Mulberry: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- B y   B e n   M a r t i n   a n d   A d a m   E w i n g
-- 2010-10-07T06:52:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-06/british-airways-investec-shell-ted-baker-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  climbed 45.63, or 0.8 percent,
to 5,681.39. The  FTSE All-Share Index  also rose 0.8 percent and
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  advanced 1.1 percent.  British Airways Plc  (BAY LN): Chief Executive Officer
 Willie Walsh  said he’d rather the carrier grew through mergers
than joint ventures, though alliances are easier to arrange in
the current regulatory environment. The shares jumped 4.5
percent to 266.1 pence.  Carillion Plc  (CLLN LN): The manager of buildings for BT
Group Plc and the British armed services said third-quarter
trading was “in line” with its expectations. The shares
increased 1.9 percent to 327.3 pence.  Investec Plc  (INVP LN): The South African private bank
started offering 130 million pounds ($206.61 million) of
securities backed by U.K. non-conforming mortgages in the first
public sale of the bonds since 2007. The stock advanced 1.3
percent to 512.5 pence.  Kazakhmys Plc  (KAZ LN): Credit Suisse Group AG is managing
the sale of 9.35 million Kazakhmys shares, or a 1.75 percent
stake in the company, according to terms of the transaction
obtained by Bloomberg News.  The shares are being sold by  Orleans  Trade & Investment
Corp., the terms show. In April 2007, Vladimir Ni, a non-
executive director of Kazakhmys who died last month, transferred
9.35 million shares to OTIC, according to the terms. The shares
gained 3.9 percent to 1,483 pence.  Mulberry Group Plc  (MUL LN): The maker of Bayswater luxury
handbags said sales and profit for the year ending March 31
“are expected to significantly exceed market expectations.”
The shares were unchanged at 397.5 pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc  (RDSA LN): Europe’s biggest oil
company said it applied to drill one well off the coast of
Alaska next year, resuming exploration in the U.S. Arctic that
was halted by court rulings and the Gulf of Mexico spill. The
shares gained 1.7 percent to 1,972 pence.  Ted Baker Plc  (TBK LN): The clothing company that dressed
James Bond actor Daniel Craig in “Casino Royale” said first-
half profit increased 24 percent on higher retail sales in the
U.K. and Europe. Net income rose to 5.36 million pounds for the
28 weeks to Aug. 14, from 4.32 million pounds a year earlier.
The stock climbed 1.6 percent to 620 pence.  Vedanta Resources Plc  (VED LN): London-based miner Vedanta
Resources said it reviewed its capital spending program because
it doesn’t have clearance to mine bauxite at Niyamgiri in India.
The shares advanced 1.2 percent to 2,223 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
